On 1 September, a storm warning signal has been issued by the Macao authorities for Typhoon Saola. For the latest information check Macao’s Meteorological and Geophysical Bureau’s website.
Transport services have been disrupted so check with your provider ahead of travel and be prepared to change your plans. Individuals are advised to remain indoors until the storm warning signal is below T8.
See our tropical cyclones page for advice about how to prepare effectively and what to do if you’re likely to be affected by a hurricane or tropical cyclone.
The typhoon season normally runs from April to October. Typhoons very occasionally hit Macao and may cause flooding and landslides. Warning is given in advance. Public offices shut down when the ‘Typhoon 8’ signal is hoisted. You should follow advice issued by the local authorities.
Monitor local and international weather updates from the World Meteorological Organisation, the China Meteorological Administration and the Japan Meteorological Agency.
